description:
## Severity
Minor
## Dimension
decoupling
## Location
src/services/feature_flags.rs:57-78
## Violation
Every is_enabled call performs a std::env::var lookup, allocates a String for the env-key, and uppercases the flag name. Quoted lines:

    fn env_override(name: &str) -> Option<bool> {
        let upper = name.to_ascii_uppercase();
        let key = format!("OPENCLAUDIA_FEATURE_{upper}");
        let raw = std::env::var(&key).ok()?;
        ...
    }

    impl FeatureFlagSource for StaticFlags {
        fn is_enabled(&self, name: &str) -> bool {
            if let Some(env) = Self::env_override(name) {
                return env;
            }
            self.entries.get(name).copied().unwrap_or(false)
        }
    }

This couples FlagSource to process-global state (env vars are not thread-isolated; another component can `set_var` mid-flight, which is also `unsafe` in modern Rust). Performance: a feature flag checked inside a per-token loop becomes O(n) env-var syscalls. Reasoning: the trait's "opt-in via map" contract leaks "and also via env" with no way for a consumer to opt out — a test cannot deterministically test a flag without leaking env state across tests (the test code does serialise on `env_lock()`, confirming the design pain).
## Mandated refactor
Snapshot env-var overrides at construction time inside StaticFlags::new (walk `OPENCLAUDIA_FEATURE_*` once, merge into entries with the env value winning). Make is_enabled a pure map lookup. Move the runtime override to an explicit `EnvOverlay` source that wraps a delegate flag-source — composability without surprise mutability.
## Filed from QA review dispatch
